+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Jt3jaHa8cEjbprtrHa2ZhV","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Good -- all tests pass and TypeScript compiles cleanly. Now let me deliver the full review.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: 8 SSG Plugins\n\n## Overall Status\n\nAll 75 tests pass. TypeScript compiles without errors. The implementations are functional and correctly satisfy the test expectations. Below I categorize findings by severity.\n\n---\n\n## CRITICAL Issues (Must Fix -- Will Cause Bugs in Production Use)\n\n### 1. `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts` -- Footnote regex only matches numeric footnote IDs\n\n**Lines 18-19, 39-41:**\n```typescript\nconst footnoteDefRegex = /^\\[\\^(\\d+)\\]:\\s*(.+)$/gm;\n// ...\ncontent = content.replace(\n  /\\[\\^(\\d+)\\]/g,\n  (_match, num: string) => `<sup><a href=\"#fn-${num}\">${num}</a></sup>`\n);\n```\n\nThe regex uses `\\d+` which only matches numeric footnote identifiers like `[^1]`. Standard Markdown footnote syntax (used by GitHub, Pandoc, and most Markdown implementations) supports alphanumeric identifiers like `[^note]` or `[^my-reference]`. Any real-world content using non-numeric footnote IDs will silently fail to be processed. The tests only cover numeric IDs, so this passes all tests, but it will break for real content.\n\n**Recommendation:** Change `\\d+` to `[\\w-]+` in all three regex patterns (definition extraction, definition removal, and inline reference replacement). The `<ol>` in the footnotes section would also need updating since non-numeric IDs do not correspond to ordered list semantics.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts` -- Admonition regex requires `:::` at the start of a line but uses `^` without guaranteed multiline context\n\n**Lines 31-36:**\n```typescript\ncontent = content.replace(\n  /^:::(\\w+)\\n([\\s\\S]*?)^:::/gm,\n  (_match, type: string, inner: string) => {\n    return `<div class=\"admonition admonition-${type}\">\\n${inner.trim()}\\n</div>`;\n  }\n);\n```\n\nThe closing `^:::` requires `:::` at the start of a line, which works because of the `m` flag. However, the inner capture `([\\s\\S]*?)` is lazy and matches the *first* occurrence of `^:::`. If content has *nested* admonitions or a line that starts with `:::` inside another admonition, the match will terminate early and produce corrupted output. This is an edge case not covered by tests, but worth noting for production use.\n\n---\n\n### 3. `/workspace/src/plugins/rss-feed.ts` -- Missing XML escaping for title and content\n\n**Lines 43-48:**\n```typescript\nreturn `<item>\n<title>${file.title}</title>\n<link>${ctx.config.baseUrl}/${file.slug}.html</link>\n${pubDate ? pubDate + '\\n' : ''}<description><![CDATA[${file.content}]]></description>\n${categories}\n</item>`;\n```\n\nThe `<title>` element is not wrapped in CDATA and has no XML entity escaping. A title containing `&`, `<`, or `>` (e.g., \"Tips & Tricks\" or \"A < B\") will produce invalid XML. The `<link>` element has the same problem -- slugs with `&` would break it. While `<description>` is correctly wrapped in CDATA, the `content` could itself contain `]]>` which would prematurely close the CDATA section.\n\nSimilarly, in `/workspace/src/plugins/rss-feed.ts` **line 38**, the `<category>` elements have no escaping.\n\nThe same problem exists in `/workspace/src/plugins/sitemap.ts` **line 21** -- URLs are not XML-escaped, so `&` in query strings would produce invalid XML:\n```typescript\n.map(url => `<url><loc>${url}</loc></url>`)\n```\n\n**Recommendation:** Add an XML-escaping helper function:\n```typescript\nfunction escapeXml(str: string): string {\n  return str.replace(/&/g, '&amp;').replace(/</g, '&lt;').replace(/>/g, '&gt;').replace(/\"/g, '&quot;');\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. `/workspace/src/plugins/search-index.ts` -- HTML tag stripping is fragile\n\n**Line 12:**\n```typescript\nconst plainText = file.content.replace(/<[^>]*>/g, '');\n```\n\nThis regex-based HTML stripping will fail on:\n- Attributes containing `>` characters (e.g., `<div data-expr=\"a>b\">`)\n- HTML comments (`<!-- comment -->` -- the `>` inside will cause a partial match)\n- Content with `<` that is not an HTML tag (e.g., math expressions like \"if a < b\")\n\nThe tests do not exercise these cases, so they all pass, but this will produce corrupted search index entries in real-world content. This is a well-known limitation of regex-based HTML stripping. For a production SSG, a proper HTML parser or at minimum a more robust regex would be warranted.\n\n---\n\n## IMPORTANT Issues (Should Fix)\n\n### 5. `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts` -- `marked.parse()` called synchronously without error handling\n\n**Line 45:**\n```typescript\nconst html = marked.parse(content, { async: false }) as string;\n```\n\nIf `marked.parse` throws (e.g., on malformed input or a marked internal error), the entire plugin call will throw with an unhelpful stack trace. There is no try/catch, and no fallback behavior. At minimum, wrapping this in a try/catch that returns the raw content on failure would be more defensive.\n\n---\n\n### 6. `/workspace/src/plugins/asset-pipeline.ts` -- Only rewrites `src` and `href` attributes, misses other asset references\n\n**Lines 14-29:**\n\nThe plugin only handles `src=\"./...\"` and `href=\"./...\"` patterns. It does not handle:\n- CSS `url(./...)` references in inline styles\n- `srcset=\"./...\"` attributes on responsive images\n- `poster=\"./...\"` on video elements\n- `background=\"./...\"` legacy attributes\n- Single-quoted attributes: `src='./image.png'`\n\nThe tests only cover the two implemented patterns, so they pass. But real HTML content will commonly include at least `srcset` and single-quoted variants.\n\n---\n\n### 7. `/workspace/src/plugins/taxonomy.ts` -- Tag page HTML links may produce wrong URLs for nested slugs\n\n**Line 31:**\n```typescript\n.map(f => `<li><a href=\"/${f.slug}.html\">${f.title}</a></li>`)\n```\n\nIf a file slug contains path separators (e.g., `blog/post-1`), this produces `href=\"/blog/post-1.html\"`. However, the tag page itself lives at `tags/javascript.html`. Relative vs. absolute path resolution could behave differently depending on how this HTML is served. The leading `/` makes it absolute, so this is probably fine, but worth verifying against the actual output structure.\n\n---\n\n### 8. `/workspace/src/plugins/rss-feed.ts` -- Redundant tag logic for when `tagMap` is absent\n\n**Lines 22-35:**\n```typescript\nif (file.tags && tagMap) {\n  for (const tag of file.tags) {\n    const normalized = tag.toLowerCase();\n    if (tagMap.has(normalized)) {\n      categoryTags.push(normalized);\n    }\n  }\n}\n// Also add tags even without taxonomy data\nif (file.tags && !tagMap) {\n  for (const tag of file.tags) {\n    categoryTags.push(tag.toLowerCase());\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThe first branch checks `tagMap.has(normalized)` before adding, which means tags that exist on the file but were not indexed by taxonomy (perhaps a different file introduced the tag) would be silently omitted. The two branches have inconsistent behavior: with taxonomy data, only previously-indexed tags are included; without taxonomy data, all tags are included. This inconsistency will surprise users. The simpler and more correct logic would be: always add `file.tags` lowercased, regardless of whether taxonomy data exists.\n\n---\n\n## SUGGESTIONS (Nice to Have)\n\n### 9. All plugins -- No input validation or logging\n\nNone of the 8 plugins validate their inputs or produce any diagnostic output. For example:\n- `markdown-ext` does not log when it encounters malformed admonition syntax\n- `rss-feed` does not warn when `ctx.config.baseUrl` is empty\n- `dev-server` silently produces an empty config when there is nothing to serve\n\nAdding a lightweight logging mechanism (even just `console.warn` for unexpected states) would significantly improve debuggability.\n\n---\n\n### 10. `/workspace/src/plugins/dev-server.ts` -- `searchIndexPath` is empty string instead of `null`/`undefined` when absent\n\n**Lines 30-32:**\n```typescript\nconst searchIndexPath = ctx.output.has('search-index.json')\n  ? '/search-index.json'\n  : '';\n```\n\nUsing empty string as a sentinel for \"no search index\" is a weak convention. Consumers of `dev-server-config` would need to check `searchIndexPath !== ''` rather than the more idiomatic `searchIndexPath != null`. This is a minor API design issue, but using `null` would be clearer.\n\n---\n\n### 11. `/workspace/src/plugins/rss-feed.ts` -- RSS feed does not include `<description>` at channel level\n\nThe RSS 2.0 specification requires a `<description>` element inside `<channel>`. The generated feed omits it:\n\n```xml\n<channel>\n<title>Test Site</title>\n<link>https://example.com</link>\n... items ...\n</channel>\n```\n\nWhile many RSS readers will still parse this, it is technically invalid per the spec. Adding `<description>${ctx.config.title}</description>` (or a dedicated config field) would fix it.\n\n---\n\n### 12. `/workspace/src/plugins/sitemap.ts` -- Sitemap does not exclude non-content files\n\nThe sitemap includes *every* key in `ctx.output` except `sitemap.xml` itself. This means `search-index.json` and `feed.xml` will appear as `<url>` entries. While `feed.xml` is arguably reasonable, `search-index.json` is a data file, not a page users should navigate to. The test at line 61-68 actually expects `feed.xml` to be included, so this is by design, but consider whether data files belong in a sitemap.\n\n---\n\n### 13. Code consistency -- Mixed patterns across plugins\n\n- `markdown-ext` checks `if (!content)` (line 13) for empty/falsy content, but `syntax-highlight` would throw on `file.content.replace(...)` if `file.content` were ever `undefined` (though the type says it is `string`, so this is unlikely).\n- `search-index` references `file.content` without a null guard, while `markdown-ext` explicitly handles the empty case.\n- Some plugins use `_ctx` for unused parameters (`markdown-ext`, `syntax-highlight`), while `asset-pipeline` uses `ctx` even when needed. This is fine, just noting the consistency.\n\n---\n\n## Summary Table\n\n| # | Severity | Plugin | Issue |\n|---|----------|--------|-------|\n| 1 | Critical | markdown-ext | Footnote regex limited to numeric IDs only |\n| 2 | Critical | markdown-ext | Admonition regex breaks on nested/adjacent admonitions |\n| 3 | Critical | rss-feed, sitemap | No XML escaping for titles, URLs, or categories |\n| 4 | Critical | search-index | Regex-based HTML stripping fails on edge cases |\n| 5 | Important | markdown-ext | No error handling around `marked.parse()` |\n| 6 | Important | asset-pipeline | Misses `srcset`, single-quoted attrs, CSS `url()` |\n| 7 | Important | taxonomy | Tag page links assume flat slug structure |\n| 8 | Important | rss-feed | Inconsistent tag inclusion with/without taxonomy data |\n| 9 | Suggestion | all | No input validation or diagnostic logging |\n| 10 | Suggestion | dev-server | Empty string sentinel instead of `null` |\n| 11 | Suggestion | rss-feed | Missing required `<description>` in RSS `<channel>` |\n| 12 | Suggestion | sitemap | Includes data files (JSON) as sitemap URLs |\n| 13 | Suggestion | all | Minor inconsistencies in null/empty guarding |\n\n## What Was Done Well\n\n- All 75 tests pass; TypeScript compiles with zero errors.\n- The plugin architecture cleanly follows the `Plugin` interface with proper `hooks`, `name`, `version`, and `dependencies`.\n- The `dependencies` arrays are correctly declared (e.g., `rss-feed` depends on `markdown-ext` and `taxonomy`; `dev-server` depends on `asset-pipeline` and `search-index`).\n- The `transformContent` hooks correctly produce new objects via spread (`{ ...file, content }`) rather than mutating the input, which is a good functional pattern.\n- The `ctx.data` shared store is used effectively for cross-plugin communication (taxonomy tag map, asset manifest, dev-server config).\n- Edge cases like empty content, missing dates, and missing asset data are handled in most plugins.\n- The code is concise and readable, with clear intent in each plugin."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: aa4d863 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 35545\ntool_uses: 19\nduration_ms: 96500</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"64da79a0-d75b-41db-a1c0-c69309d380c0","uuid":"caf30108-5672-4522-b30e-a097ee565a71","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review the implementation of the 8 SSG plugins I just created. The diff is between base commit 8a7ba32 and HEAD. \n\nFocus on:\n1. Correctness - do all implementations match what the tests expect?\n2. Edge cases - any missed edge cases?\n3. Code quality - any issues?\n\nRead each plugin file in src/plugins/ and each corresponding test file in tests/plugins/ to verify correctness. Check for HIGH PRIORITY issues that could cause test failures or bugs.\n\nFiles to review:\n- src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts\n- src/plugins/asset-pipeline.ts\n- src/plugins/syntax-highlight.ts\n- src/plugins/taxonomy.ts\n- src/plugins/rss-feed.ts\n- src/plugins/search-index.ts\n- src/plugins/sitemap.ts\n- src/plugins/dev-server.ts","agentId":"aa4d863","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Good -- all tests pass and TypeScript compiles cleanly. Now let me deliver the full review.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: 8 SSG Plugins\n\n## Overall Status\n\nAll 75 tests pass. TypeScript compiles without errors. The implementations are functional and correctly satisfy the test expectations. Below I categorize findings by severity.\n\n---\n\n## CRITICAL Issues (Must Fix -- Will Cause Bugs in Production Use)\n\n### 1. `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts` -- Footnote regex only matches numeric footnote IDs\n\n**Lines 18-19, 39-41:**\n```typescript\nconst footnoteDefRegex = /^\\[\\^(\\d+)\\]:\\s*(.+)$/gm;\n// ...\ncontent = content.replace(\n  /\\[\\^(\\d+)\\]/g,\n  (_match, num: string